          "body": "The twin rhetorical questions of verse 3 — 'Who may ascend the hill of the Lord? Who may stand in His holy place?' — belong to a recognized genre in the ancient Near Eastern world: the entrance liturgy, or 'temple gate liturgy.' Scholars compare Psalm 15, Isaiah 33:14-16, Micah 6:6-8, and Ezekiel 18:5-9 as parallel formulations where the worshiper is interrogated at the threshold. The answer in verse 4 is fourfold and moves deliberately from outside in. 'Clean hands' — the external conduct is innocent; no theft, no violence, no oppression marks the worshiper's public life. 'Pure heart' — the interior motivation corresponds to the exterior act; the bar levav (pure, clear heart) is not divided between God and something else. 'Has not lifted up his soul to falsehood' — no idolatry in the deepest sense: the soul's gravitational pull is toward Yahweh, not toward the empty and vain things (*shav*) that compete for it. 'Has not sworn deceitfully' — the worshiper's speech in God's name is trustworthy; covenant-oath integrity is required because God Himself is a covenant-keeper. John Calvin notes that these four are not a ladder of merit but a portrait of moral correspondence: the one who approaches the Holy must bear some family resemblance to the Holy (Commentary on the Psalms, vol. 1, 1557). The same fourfold criterion makes clear that external ritual without internal transformation is precisely what this psalm does not accept."
