          "body": "Verses 5-6 move from the individual portrait of v.4 to the community this portrait describes. The qualified worshiper 'shall receive blessing from the Lord and righteousness from the God of his salvation' (v.5) — two gifts that correspond to the two dimensions of the divine name. Blessing (*berakhah*) covers the relational, material, and spiritual flourishing that Yahweh promises to His covenant people. Righteousness (*tsedaqah*) carries the forensic weight of vindication — the worshiper is declared right before the God who is Himself righteous. Crucially, these are received, not achieved; the moral qualifications of v.4 describe the posture of the one who comes, not the currency with which the gifts are purchased. Verse 6 then names this community: 'the generation of those who seek Him, who seek Your face — even Jacob.' The sudden shift to second person ('Your face') is the psalm's first moment of direct address — the worshiper has moved from describing God to speaking to Him. Jacob is the covenant name, suggesting not moral perfection (Jacob the patriarch was far from it) but election and promise. Charles Spurgeon observes that Jacob the seeker is the paradigm: his wrestling at Peniel (Genesis 32:26) — 'I will not let you go unless you bless me' — is the portrait of the generation this psalm names (The Treasury of David, vol. 1)."
