          "body": "The psalm's final verse answers the repeated challenge with the highest possible title: 'The Lord of hosts, He is the King of glory.' The Lord of hosts (*Yahweh Tsabaoth*) is the psalm's supreme identification of the processional King. The title, which appears over 280 times in the Hebrew Bible, denotes Yahweh as the commander of every army — angelic, celestial, military. He who demands moral purity of those ascending His hill (vv. 3-4) and He who is mighty in battle (v.8) are the same Person. The entry of the King of glory is therefore simultaneously an act of holy condescension (the High King entering the gates He owns) and military triumph (the warrior returning victorious). The christological resonance is unavoidable for the New Testament reader. The early church read Psalm 24 at Easter and at the Ascension — the King of glory who entered Jerusalem on a donkey (Matthew 21:9), who descended to the tomb, and who ascended to the Father is the Lord of hosts of Psalm 24:10. D. A. Carson notes that the Psalter consistently operates typologically: David's liturgical psalms reach beyond their original occasion toward a King David himself could only partially embody (For the Love of God, vol. 1). The final *Selah* arrests the movement entirely: the declaration has been made. There is nothing left to add."
