        "title": "Creation as the ground of Yahweh's absolute sovereignty",
        "range": "24:1-2",
        "excerpt": "The earth is the Lord's, and all it contains, the world, and those who dwell in it. For He has founded it upon the seas and established it upon the rivers.",
        "body": "The opening declaration is the psalm's theological non-negotiable. Everything that follows — the moral demands, the gate-calls, the royal title — stands on this foundation: Yahweh owns the earth because He made it. The 'for' (*ki*) at the beginning of verse 2 is a causal connector: the ownership claim of v.1 rests on the creative act of v.2. This is not circular; it is the Old Testament's consistent logic: creator-rights equal owner-rights (cf. Genesis 14:19; Deuteronomy 10:14; Psalm 50:12; Nehemiah 9:6).\n\nThe cosmological language of verse 2 — founding upon seas, establishing upon rivers — draws deliberately on ancient Near Eastern cosmological imagery. Israel's neighbors pictured the earth as a disk resting on cosmic waters; Yahweh's founding (*yasad*) and establishing (*kun*) the earth on those waters is His act of imposing order on what could otherwise be chaos. Unlike the Babylonian Enuma Elish, where creation emerges from the death of a chaos monster, Psalm 24 pictures Yahweh meeting no resistance: He simply founded it. The seas and rivers obey.\n\nThe pastoral weight of vv.1-2 is often underestimated because the verses seem merely introductory. They are not. They establish the moral basis of everything that follows. The question 'Who may ascend the hill of the Lord?' (v.3) only makes sense if the hill belongs to Yahweh absolutely — and it does, because the whole earth does. The worshiper does not come to a neutral zone that the community has dedicated to worship; he comes to the King's own hill, on the King's own terms, in the King's own world.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Erets* (earth) and *tevel* (world) are the Psalter's standard pair for totality — neither term is redundant. *Yasad* (to found) and *kun* (to establish, fix firmly) are the vocabulary of irreversible order. *Melo* (fullness, all it contains) — everything the earth holds, including its people — is encompassed in the ownership claim."
